### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

compiler

### Is this a regression?

Yes

### Description

When using `:where(:host(...))` in component styles, Angular 19's CSS rewriter incorrectly places `_ngcontent-*` attributes in the generated CSS selector

This causes host-level styles not to match the intended elements anymore. It works fine in Angular 18. 

Original css:
```

:where(:host[data-display=inline]) {
  display: inline;
  width: auto;
}

:where(:host[data-display=inline])[data-color] {
  display: inline-block;
}
```


Expected (Angular 18 generated css)
```
:where([data-display='inline'])[_nghost-ng-c202844894] {
  display: inline;
  width: auto;
}
:where([data-display='inline'])[data-color][_nghost-ng-c202844894] {
  display: inline-block;
}
```


Actual (Angular 19 generated css)
```
:where([data-display=inline][_nghost-ng-c3267546756]) {
  display: inline;
  width: auto;
}
[_ngcontent-ng-c3267546756]:where([data-display=inline][_nghost-ng-c3267546756])[data-color] {
  display: inline-block;
}
```

Notice that the second selector incorrectly starts with
`[_ngcontent-ng-c3267546756]:where(...),`
which targets child content, not the host element.
As a result, the host element no longer matches this rule.


